<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> True science, following The Scientific Method (TM), cannot be so easily manipulated.<br>
<br>
The whole point of the scientific method is that an experiment only passes peer review when it has been proven that the results are the same EVERY SINGLE TIME, and that the experiment did not provide a bias or loophole by which the result would remain inconclusive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree 100%, but who is doing  all these non-biased scientific studies?  NORML?  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> yah, riiiiight.,/i]  The government?  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> uh-huh..su</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Non-profit organizations?  Those organizations get their money from somewhere, and usually that money comes with thick nasty strings, especially where things like drugs are concerned.  I honestly can think of NO organization who would have the ability to do such a study on drug use and which is immune to budget-induced bias. <br>
<br>
 I'm going to assume, however, that such an organization exists, and that the studies also exist.  Who is going to publish and distribute these studies?  Our mainstream media?  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Hell yah! </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> We all know how unbiased and non-corruptible the media is.  Wait...maybe NORML would underwrite such a publication.  Only if it said what they wanted, is my guess.  Oh...I know...our government would publish the results of the studies no matter what the results, right?  <br>
<br>
I don't consider myself a cynic by any means, but I honestly don't believe that such things as non-biased studies about drug use exist.  In the absence of them, I use human experience to base my opinions on.  I try to always use the best available data.<br>
<br>
Oh..and by the way Wayfarer.  A few years ago I would have argued exactly the same points that you are.  Since then I've become considerably more educated and exposed to a larger portion of the world.  It makes me sad a little bit.<br>
<br>
